<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED CAR THIEF INJURES POLICE STATION CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 22 (CNA) 05/22/07  20:51:45 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The head of a Taipei County police station suffered a knife wound
to the chest when he stopped a suspected car thief for
questioning early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tsai Huang-chi, head of the Daguan police station in Banchiao
city, was rushed to Far Eastern Memorial Hospital, where he was
treated and declared in satisfactory condition.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that at about 1 a.m. when he was off duty, he
spotted a suspicious looking man near a convenience store who
seemed to be trying to steal a car.
</P>
<P>
According to the police chief, as he approached the man to
question him, the suspect, who appeared to be about 30 years old
and stood about 170 cm tall, suddenly produced a knife and
stabbed him in the chest before running away.
</P>
<P>
Passersby called police who rushed Tsai to the hospital, where he
was treated for a collapsed lung.
</P>
<P>
Taipei County Magistrate Chou Hsi-wei, who visited Tsai in the
hospital, urged the police to bring Tsai's assailant to justice.
</P>
